  "prompt": "Why are sigma anti-bonding orbitals higher in energy than pi anti-bonding orbitals?",
  "response": "The relative energy levels of sigma (\u03c3) and pi (\u03c0) anti-bonding orbitals are determined by the nature of the interactions between the atomic orbitals that form these molecular orbitals. Here's a breakdown of why sigma anti-bonding orbitals are generally higher in energy than pi anti-bonding orbitals:\n\n### 1. **Bonding and Anti-Bonding Interactions:**\n   - In molecular orbital theory, when two atomic orbitals combine, they form bonding (lower energy) and anti-bonding (higher energy) molecular orbitals.\n   - **Sigma (\u03c3) bonding orbitals** are formed by the head-on overlap of atomic orbitals (e.g., s-s, s-p, or p-p overlap along the internuclear axis). This overlap is strong and results in a significant lowering of energy in the bonding orbital.\n   - **Pi (\u03c0) bonding orbitals** are formed by the side-on overlap of p orbitals. This overlap is less strong than sigma overlap, so the energy lowering in the \u03c0 bonding orbital is less pronounced than in the \u03c3 bonding orbital.\n\n### 2. **Anti-Bonding Orbitals:**\n   - **Sigma anti-bonding (\u03c3\\*)** orbitals arise from the out-of-phase (destructive) overlap of atomic orbitals in a head-on manner. Because the original \u03c3 bonding interaction was strong, the anti-bonding interaction is correspondingly very destabilizing, leading to a high-energy \u03c3\\* orbital.\n   - **Pi anti-bonding (\u03c0\\*)** orbitals arise from the out-of-phase overlap in a side-on manner. Since the \u03c0 bonding interaction was weaker, the anti-bonding \u03c0\\* orbital is not as destabilized as the \u03c3\\* orbital.\n\n### 3. **Energy Comparison:**\n   - The **\u03c3\\* anti-bonding orbital** is higher in energy than the **\u03c0\\* anti-bonding orbital** because the sigma bonding interaction is stronger, so the anti-bonding interaction is correspondingly more destabilizing.\n   - In contrast, the **\u03c0\\*** anti-bonding orbital is less destabilized because the \u03c0 bonding interaction was weaker to begin with.\n\n### 4. **Molecular Orbital Diagram:**\n   - In a typical diatomic molecular orbital diagram (e.g., for O\u2082 or N\u2082), the \u03c3\\* orbital is the highest-energy orbital, followed by the \u03c0\\* orbitals. This ordering reflects the greater destabilization of the \u03c3\\* orbital due to the stronger sigma bonding interaction.\n\n### Summary:\nSigma anti-bonding orbitals are higher in energy than pi anti-bonding orbitals because the sigma bonding interaction is stronger, making the corresponding anti-bonding interaction more destabilizing. In contrast, the weaker pi bonding interaction leads to less destabilization in the pi anti-bonding orbital.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
